WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African-American History and Culture.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:13.000
Hello, Pedro.

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:19.000
Today is Wednesday, July 6, 2011.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:27.000
My name is Joe Mosnier of the Southern Wall of the History Program at the University of North Carolina UNC-Chapel Hill-Chapel Hill.

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:31.000
I'm in Greensboro, North Carolina with the out of Rick John Bishop.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:36.000
We are here to conduct an interview in the Civil Rights History Project,

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:45.000
which is a joint undertaking of the National Museum of African-American History and Culture inside the Smithsonian Institution and the Library of Congress.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:53.000
We're on the campus of Bennett College with Provost Esther Terry and Dr. Terri, it's just a privilege to be with you.

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:55.000
Thank you for sitting now with us.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:56.000
Thank you for having me.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:01.000
I'm going to bring some time on. I know you're very busy schedule. It's really nice to be with you.

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:11.000
I thought we'd start today if you would, but maybe just a description of your family and life as a child of a war in California to range across that.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:14.000
Yes, it was a wonderful time.

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:18.000
I am the youngest of 12.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:36.000
So I always, always, from the time I opened my eyes, had many hands around to pick me up when I fell, to punch me out sometimes when we had one day wanted to show that they were all bigger and stronger and so much growner than I was.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:39.000
But it was a good life. We were farmers.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:51.000
My dad was Mary Alexander. My mom was Mary Alexander. My mom had gone through, had started to enter normal school.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:02:01.000
In those days, that was where one went, many, many women went to prepare to come back, to teach to the community.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:08.000
My mom had gotten to normal school, but after her first year there, her mom died.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:14.000
And she was the oldest of her siblings, so she was brought home to take care of them.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:21.000
That was an unfortunate thing because she always, always wanted to go finish and to teach.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:33.000
But she didn't, and she married my father as a second husband. Her first husband died in the flu epidemic of 1917.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:43.000
My mom was married and to author Hunt, and they had three children.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:52.000
She lived with author and her three children in Richmond, Virginia. She actually was born in Warren County, North Carolina as well.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:58.000
She had left Warren County, North Carolina with her husband, and they had taken a residence in Richmond, Virginia.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:00.000
He died of the flu.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:14.000
Meanwhile, my dad, who had grown up in Virginia right across the line, if you know where my home is, is right on the border of Virginia.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:21.000
My father had married a wife, and he had three children as well.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:26.000
He lost his wife in that epidemic and his three children.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:35.000
My mom lost her husband, but her three children survived. So she moved home as one was want to do.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:41.000
It was a thing to do. She moved home now. She was a woman with three children to raise, and no husband.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:48.000
So she moved back to her home in Warren County, North Carolina, and she met my dad.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:58.000
And they were married. They met him were married. And he then started to share crop, and she went to the farm with him.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:07.000
He raised all of those children, her three children as his own. And to that union, as they say, they were nine more children born.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:14.000
So I actually am the youngest of 12 children, all of us were my mother's children.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:33.000
But actually all of us were my dad's children too, because he loved us all. And that we grew up there as a family on a big old farm that my dad worked for in the early years as a sharecropper, but soon decided to work with the owner to try to buy.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:48.000
And did succeeded in buying the land. And that land has remained in our family from from the time there. My dad died in 1970, and mom died in 1985.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:56.000
And we have kept the land. Now I regret to say all of my siblings are dead. I'm the last of them.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:07.000
So the farm means a great deal to me in North, that farm in, in Wise, North Carolina, North Carolina, because I choose where I am in Wise, North Carolina, North Carolina, the farm.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:24.000
And the children there are nieces and nephews. They are the children of my brothers and sisters. And so as we did when one sibling was out of place, when they were living, the other siblings looked after the children.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:39.000
So I only have one son, biologically speaking, but I have a lot of children when you consider all of the nieces and nephews and their children and their children's children. So we are many.

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:42.000
When Mr. Father is able to make that purchase?

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:50.000
In 1945, I think, in 1945, dad made that.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:54.000
What about schooling and church when you were a child?

00:05:54.000 --> 00:06:00.000
Well, very important. The church, particularly.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:15.000
My mom was a serious, serious churchgoer. But she wasn't fanatic about that. And so we had the teachings of the church. More than the preachings, I think.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:23.000
Can I make those, those, that distinction? I think my mom always said to us when she wanted us to be good, good children.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:32.000
She would say, I'd rather see a sermon than to hear one. That was her philosophy. My mom wasn't interested so much.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:43.000
I mean, we went to church daily, regularly, not daily, but regularly. When it was time for us to go, every time for us to go to church, we went to church.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:56.000
But it was, it wasn't oppressive church. She understood if we kind of sat with the girls our age and giggled a little bit. She understood if we were our age.

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:11.000
She didn't make us, she didn't make us burdened by the church, but she always wanted us to be good. And so she paid more attention to how going to Sunday school than to hear preaching so much.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:19.000
But Sunday school was important. We learned, we learned a lot. And she would ask us when we came home from Sunday school, what did you learn?

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:33.000
And she always asked us to apply that to our lives. My mom was always, we used to call her the, how would you feel if mom, you know, behind her back, of course, we never said anything like that in the fun of our face.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:43.000
She would always say, if we, you know, did something, she didn't think was nice. She would say to someone else, how would you feel if that happened to you and she'd make us think about it?

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:50.000
How would you feel if someone took your lunch? How would you feel if someone walked away from you and kept you from playing?

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:59.000
We learned early, and I don't know where we learned it, but one of the things we did that I often think about, you know, I asked myself, is it an eight, you know?

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:10.000
We learned that separation was painful. If, for instance, if we were without a little girlfriend and we weren't allowed to fight, we never did that.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:20.000
But we learned very early that if we said, don't play with Sally, or we, or, you know, we get the group on my side against Sally.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:31.000
We're not going to play with her. That's how it would hurt so badly. I don't know how we learned that isolation was such a powerful tool to use against someone.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:37.000
But we did. And my mom would always say, how would you feel if somebody did that to you? How would you feel if somebody did that to you?

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:42.000
So we used to call her, or how would you feel if we never tell her that?

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:46.000
What was the school experience that you had as a child?

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:58.000
Oh, we excelled in school. I liked school. I always did. My sisters and brothers, I really, I don't know that they liked school as much as I did.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:08.000
But we went because my mom, you see, thought it was important for us to go to school. And because we worked on a farm, we weren't always allowed to go every day.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:21.000
Sometimes the crops would just need to be taken in. You know, we just needed to save the crops. But mom would work so very, very hard to do all of it.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:27.000
To make up for our not being in the field. She would get up in the morning and go to the field with my dad.

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:36.000
And she would work. Oh, she would work so hard. She'd pick cotton. What a terrible thing to do pick. But she would pick cotton. She would pick cotton.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:49.000
To make up for the fact that we weren't there. And then we were told to come from school directly from school and change our clothes really, really quickly and run, run, run to the field to because mom would be there working so hard.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:58.000
And then when we got to the field to help pick the cotton, she would go to the house to make us something good for supper. She always did good supper for us.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:07.000
I had a good life. I didn't know I was a poor girl. I didn't think about that too much.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:17.000
How closely connected was the black community in the area of Wise, North Carolina? Because of course farmland sketch can be depending on population. That's fairly spread out.

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:30.000
Well, there were. But but you see we had the church and we had the school. They they were centers for the activity of the community.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:52.000
And we we took advantage of those my my parents would come to school for for Easter programs. They would come for programs that we had in the evenings where their children, you know, performed and they saw their children. My parents were very much as were the parents of other members in the community very much involved with the school.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:11:05.000
Not like now, not so much so is that the case now as I think about it as I go home to see. But when I grew up parents were very much involved in in the school of very much.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:18.000
Sometimes we did and sometimes we didn't. I think the times when we didn't was when my brothers were away and not we didn't have a brother to drive.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:32.000
And my dad didn't ever drive. He never ever drove and I don't know why that was but he just never drove a car. Never was licensed. But if when my brothers were there before they would go off to the army or go somewhere we would have a car.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:44.000
I just suggested something I was interested. I know there are 11 siblings ahead of you. But in broad one one very important part about about your life history courses you're the first in your family to go to four year college.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:45.000
Yes.

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:49.000
And what were the life paths of taken by some of your older siblings?

00:11:49.000 --> 00:12:07.000
Oh, we didn't have money to go to college. I like to talk about this part of it. I'm not very much willing and coming forth coming to talking about my family very much. But I always want to say that I always thought how ironic.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:23.000
I thought always that I was not the smartest of my siblings. I was just the luckiest one in this regard. There was never money. There weren't many scholarships you know then as there are now for black kids to go off to school.

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:42.000
So my brothers and sisters will go up and they went off. We had a thriving much more thriving than now manufacturing country then. Manufacturing was big and so they got job in factories. One of my brothers worked two of my brothers worked at Ford Motors.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:13:03.000
One of them you know my brother I had a brother who would always well he would never drive any car. There wasn't a general motor car and he would always say why didn't you get a general motor car. There were loyal to the factories that they worked in and some of them worked. I had a brother who worked in Newport News, Virginia for a very long time.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:23.000
For a long time then made a good living. I had another brother who worked in the system, the school system of New York. I think he might have been a janitor. They call him something else now. Engineers of some kind of another thing he was probably just a janitor but he took pride in his job.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:33.000
And they were proud that they were never fired from anything and they all bought their homes and took care of their wives in that way.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:37.000
How did it come to pass that your family was able to send you to Bennett?

00:13:37.000 --> 00:14:04.000
Well, farmers got social security. It's as simple as that. My sense of these things sometimes when I think about them is that it's so connected and so unknown by people who sit in decision making positions in the world. They don't quite know how one thing affects another.

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:16.000
When did the farmers get social security in 1957? Until that time, farmers did not get social security. They wanted.

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:31.000
When farmers got social security, the recipients of social security were able to get it retroactive to the time that they turned 65.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:47.000
I remember going home and working so hard, helping my parents. Not just my parents but helping the people in the neighborhood go and sign up to prove their ages. I learned so much about the Bible.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:15:08.000
I remember where names were recorded. Most of the people in my community had been born at home with midwives and so the midwife would. Here's another thing. The midwife would have four babies delivered in a week and she'd have to go all the way into town to register them.

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:27.000
I would go to the baby boy and I would turn them all in when I get a lot. There's all kinds of stories that I loved hearing about my folk. That person was not really born on that day. That person was born on another day.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:39.000
That's how that goes. We had good times talking about how the midwife misnamed somebody or forgot, spelled the name incorrectly. There are those stories.

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:52.000
Everybody knew everybody in my neighborhood. We got together and I learned my first chance to figure out how to convince somebody about your age.

00:15:52.000 --> 00:16:16.000
If you don't have it in the courthouse, if you don't have a birth certificate, you should go to the family Bible because most people entered the deaths and births. If you have to go looking for a history of the people, find deaths in births, find a Bible or some other religious place in the Bible. The black community was the Bible.

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:35.000
They could tell you what year a flood came or when a tornado came and killed three kids or these catastrophic in nature, these catastrophic things in nature would be landmarks that would help prove their age.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:47.000
They could help some people prove that they were at least 65 and it's to establish when they turned 65 so that they could get their checks and begin to get social security.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:17:06.000
When my mom said, when my dad got a check, my mom said, this one would go to college. This one actually had no choice to go to college when I think about it. I think I might not have survived. I was so disappointed in her and that would have killed me.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:21.000
She was so much and only then did I know that she had wanted every single one of those kids to go to school. She engaged with us in the evenings when we did our lessons.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:31.000
The lessons were very important for us to do and she used to spell with us. One was a terrific speller. She would spell with us, spell our names out.

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:37.000
She would spell anything we'd have contest. We spent a lot of time together as a family.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:52.000
I'm interested to get a sense as best you can recall this and think about how other persons might have given a description below what you like as a 17-year-old thinking about heading up to college.

00:17:52.000 --> 00:18:00.000
But who did you have a set of well-formulated ambitions at that time? Did you know what you wanted to study?

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:10.000
No, I was going to teach. Something is general. I really don't recall. I think you would have asked someone else.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:23.000
Here's what I don't think I was. I don't think I was as independent of my family as I might have been.

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:34.000
I think I was always maybe too late thinking independent of what my mother needed, what my father needed, and how we would work together.

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:40.000
You see, growing up, we all talked about how we're going to all work and we're going to own the land.

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:52.000
We're going to own the land. So it was always a we that when we talked about the things we were going to do, always at the center of it was we were going to get the land and dad's going to finish paying for the land and then we're going to get a car

00:18:52.000 --> 00:19:01.000
and then we're going to get a big house and then we're going to get. So we was propelled there.

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:09.000
It propelled me in my thinking. I think maybe in 17 I didn't think so much about going off to do anything. I knew I was going to teach.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:13.000
I think. I was going to who I was going to teach and why is of course.

