My mom was always, we used to call her the, how would you feel if mom, you know, behind her back, of course.

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:40.000
We never said anything like that in front of our face.

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:44.000
But she would always say, if we did something, she didn't think was nice.

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:47.000
She would say to someone else, how would you feel if that happened to you?

00:26:47.000 --> 00:26:49.000
And she would make us think about it.

00:26:49.000 --> 00:26:51.000
How would you feel if someone took your lunch?

00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:55.000
How would you feel if someone walked away from you and kept you from playing?

00:26:55.000 --> 00:26:57.000
We learned early, and I don't know where we learned it.

00:26:57.000 --> 00:27:04.000
But one of the things we did that I often think about, you know, I ask myself, is it innate, you know?

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:09.000
But we learned that separation was painful.

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:14.000
If, for instance, if we were with our little girlfriends and we weren't allowed to fight.

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:17.000
We never did that.

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:26.000
But we learned very early that if we said, don't play with Sally, or we get the group on my side against Sally.

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:30.000
We're not going to play with her, that Sally would hurt so badly.

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:38.000
I don't know how we learned that isolation was such a powerful tool to use against someone.

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:39.000
But we did.

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:42.000
And my mom would always say, how would you feel if somebody did that to you?

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:44.000
How would you feel if somebody did that to you?

00:27:44.000 --> 00:27:49.000
So we used to call her, or how would you feel if we didn't have a child in that?

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:53.000
What was the school experience that you had as a child?

00:27:53.000 --> 00:27:55.000
Oh, we excelled in school.

00:27:55.000 --> 00:27:58.000
I liked school. I always did.

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:05.000
My sisters and brothers, I really, I don't know that they liked school as much as I did.

00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:10.000
But we went because my mom, you see, thought it was important for us to go to school.

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:15.000
And because we worked on a farm, we weren't always allowed to go every day.

00:28:15.000 --> 00:28:19.000
Sometimes the crops would just need to be taken in.

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:22.000
We just needed to save the crops.

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:28.000
But mom would work so very, very hard to do all of it,

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:31.000
to make up for our not being in the field.

00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:34.000
She would get up in the morning and go to the field with my dad,

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:36.000
and she would work, oh, she would work so hard.

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:37.000
She'd pick cotton.

00:28:37.000 --> 00:28:39.000
What a terrible thing to do to pick cotton.

00:28:39.000 --> 00:28:40.000
But she would pick cotton.

00:28:40.000 --> 00:28:41.000
She would pick cotton.

00:28:41.000 --> 00:28:46.000
She would pick cotton to make up for the fact that we weren't there.

00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:51.000
And then we were told to come from school directly from school and change our clothes really, really quickly

00:28:51.000 --> 00:28:56.000
and run, run, run to the field because mom would be there working so hard.

00:28:56.000 --> 00:29:00.000
And then when we got to the field to help pick the cotton,

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:03.000
we would go to the house to make us something good to eat for supper.

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:05.000
She always did good supper for us.

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:07.000
But I had a good life.

00:29:07.000 --> 00:29:10.000
I didn't know I was a poor girl.

00:29:10.000 --> 00:29:13.000
I didn't think about that too much.

00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:19.000
How closely connected was the black community in the area of Wise, North Carolina?

00:29:19.000 --> 00:29:24.000
Because of course, farmland sketch can be, depending on population, that's fairly spread out.

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:25.000
Well, there were.

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:30.000
But you see, we had the church and we had the school.

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:37.000
They were centers for the activity of the community.

00:29:37.000 --> 00:29:40.000
And we took advantage of those.

00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:46.000
My parents would come to school for Easter programs.

00:29:46.000 --> 00:29:52.000
They would come for programs that we had in the evenings where their children performed.

00:29:52.000 --> 00:29:53.000
And they saw their children.

00:29:53.000 --> 00:29:57.000
And my parents were very much, as were the parents of other members in the community,

00:29:57.000 --> 00:29:59.000
very much involved with the school.

00:29:59.000 --> 00:30:00.000
Not like now.

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:01.000
Not so much so.

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:03.000
Is that the case now?

00:30:03.000 --> 00:30:05.000
As I think about it, as I go home to see.

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:09.000
But when I grew up, parents were very much involved in the school of.

00:30:09.000 --> 00:30:10.000
Very much.

00:30:10.000 --> 00:30:12.000
Did you remember the call?

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:15.000
Sometimes we did and sometimes we didn't.

00:30:15.000 --> 00:30:21.000
I think the times when we didn't was when my brothers were away.

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:25.000
And we didn't have a brother to drive.

00:30:25.000 --> 00:30:27.000
My dad didn't ever drive.

00:30:27.000 --> 00:30:28.000
He never, ever drove.

00:30:28.000 --> 00:30:30.000
And I don't know why that was.

00:30:30.000 --> 00:30:31.000
But he just never drove a car.

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:32.000
He never was licensed.

00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:37.000
But when my brothers were there, before they would go off to the army or go somewhere,

00:30:37.000 --> 00:30:38.000
we would have a car.

00:30:38.000 --> 00:30:40.000
I just suggested something.

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:41.000
I was interested.

00:30:41.000 --> 00:30:44.000
I know there are 11 siblings ahead of you.

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:48.000
But in broad, one very important part about your life history course is here.

00:30:48.000 --> 00:30:51.000
You're the first in your family to go to a four-year college.

00:30:51.000 --> 00:30:52.000
Yes.

00:30:52.000 --> 00:30:56.000
And what were the life paths taken by a soldier older siblings?

00:30:56.000 --> 00:30:58.000
Oh.

00:30:58.000 --> 00:31:01.000
We didn't have money to go to college.

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:03.000
I like to talk about this part of the literature.

00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:10.000
And I'm not very much willing and coming forth coming to talking about my family very much.

00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:14.000
But I always want to say that I always thought how ironic.

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:18.000
I thought always that I was not the smartest of my siblings.

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:22.000
I was just the luckiest one in this regard.

00:31:22.000 --> 00:31:23.000
There was never money.

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:30.000
There weren't many scholarships, you know, then as there are now for black kids to go off to school.

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:33.000
So my brothers and sisters will go up and they went off.

00:31:33.000 --> 00:31:41.000
We had a thriving, much more thriving than now, manufacturing country then.

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:45.000
Manufacturing was big and so they got job in factories.

00:31:45.000 --> 00:31:49.000
One of my brothers worked, two of my brothers worked at Ford Motors.

00:31:49.000 --> 00:31:53.000
One of them, you know, my brother, I had a brother who would always,

00:31:53.000 --> 00:31:55.000
well, he would never drive any car.

00:31:55.000 --> 00:31:58.000
There wasn't a general motor's car and he would always say,

00:31:58.000 --> 00:32:00.000
why didn't you get a general motor's car?

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:04.000
There were loyal to the factories that they worked in and some of them worked.

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:10.000
I had a brother who worked in a shipyard in Newport News, Virginia for a very long time.

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:14.000
For a long time then, I made a good living.

00:32:14.000 --> 00:32:19.000
I had another brother who worked in the school system of New York.

00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:21.000
I think he might have been a janitor.

00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:25.000
They call him something else now, engineers of some kind of another.

00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:30.000
I think he was probably just a janitor, but he took pride in his job.

00:32:30.000 --> 00:32:34.000
Then they all were proud that they were never fired from anything.

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:40.000
They all bought their homes and took care of their wives in that way.

00:32:40.000 --> 00:32:44.000
How did it come to pass that your family was able to send you to Bennett?

00:32:44.000 --> 00:32:50.000
Well, farmers got social security. It's as simple as that.

00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:54.000
My sense of these things sometimes, and I think about them,

00:32:54.000 --> 00:33:03.000
is that it's so connected and so unknown by people who sit in decision-making,

00:33:03.000 --> 00:33:10.000
positions in the world. They don't quite know how one thing affects another.

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:17.000
When did the farmers get social security in 1957?

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:22.000
Until that time, farmers did not get social security.

00:33:22.000 --> 00:33:32.000
When farmers got social security, the recipients of social security were able to get it retrograde.

00:33:32.000 --> 00:33:39.000
They were able to get it retroactive to the time that they turned 65.

00:33:39.000 --> 00:33:45.000
I remember going home and working so hard, helping my parents.

00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:53.000
Not just my parents, but helping the people in the neighborhood go and sign up to prove their ages.

00:33:53.000 --> 00:33:57.000
I learned so much about the Bible, where names were recorded.

00:33:57.000 --> 00:34:04.000
I remember the people in my community had been born at home with midwives.

00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:11.000
The midwife would have four babies delivered in a week,

00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:15.000
and she'd have to go all the way into town to register them.

00:34:15.000 --> 00:34:22.000
She said, I'll turn them all in when I get a lot.

00:34:22.000 --> 00:34:31.000
There's all kinds of stories that I loved hearing about my folk who that person was not really born on that day.

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:36.000
That person was born on another day. That's how that goes.

00:34:36.000 --> 00:34:42.000
We had good times talking about how the midwife misnamed somebody or forgot,

00:34:42.000 --> 00:34:45.000
spelled the name incorrectly. They're those stories.

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:48.000
Everybody knew everybody in my neighborhood.

00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:59.000
We got together and I learned my first chance to figure out how to convince somebody about your age.

00:34:59.000 --> 00:35:04.000
If you don't have it in the courthouse, if you don't have a birth certificate,

00:35:04.000 --> 00:35:11.000
it's that you go to the family Bible because most people entered the deaths and births.

00:35:11.000 --> 00:35:18.000
If you have to go looking for a history of the people, find deaths in birth, find a Bible,

00:35:18.000 --> 00:35:22.000
or some of the religious places in the Bible, and the black community was the Bible.

00:35:22.000 --> 00:35:27.000
Then they could tell you what year a flood came,

00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:31.000
or when a tornado came and killed three kids,

00:35:31.000 --> 00:35:37.000
or these catastrophic in nature, these catastrophic things in nature,

00:35:37.000 --> 00:35:41.000
would be landmarks that would help prove their age.

00:35:41.000 --> 00:35:46.000
I helped some people prove that they were at least 65.

00:35:46.000 --> 00:35:50.000
It's to establish when they turn 65 so that they could get their checks

00:35:50.000 --> 00:35:53.000
and begin to get social security.

00:35:53.000 --> 00:35:59.000
Then my mom said, when my dad got a check, my mom said,

00:35:59.000 --> 00:36:02.000
this one will go to college.

00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:06.000
This one actually had no choice to go to college when I think about it.

00:36:06.000 --> 00:36:09.000
I think I might not have some that.

00:36:09.000 --> 00:36:13.000
I would have so disappointed her and that would have killed me, I think.

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:22.000
She's so much, and then, only then, did I know that she had wanted every single one of those kids to go to school.

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:28.000
So she engaged with us in the evenings when we did our lessons.

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:33.000
Lessons were very important for us to do, and she used to spell with us.

00:36:33.000 --> 00:36:38.000
One was a terrific speller. She would spell with us, but our names had spell.

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:40.000
They spell anything we'd see have contests.

00:36:40.000 --> 00:36:44.000
We spent a lot of time together as a family.

00:36:44.000 --> 00:36:46.000
And that's...

00:36:46.000 --> 00:36:55.000
I'm interested to get a sense as best you can recall this and think about how other persons might have given a description.

00:36:55.000 --> 00:36:57.000
But what do you like?

00:36:57.000 --> 00:37:00.000
I like to see you're all thinking about heading up to college.

00:37:00.000 --> 00:37:05.000
But who, you have a set of well-flung-related ambitions at that time?

00:37:05.000 --> 00:37:07.000
Or did you know what you wanted to study?

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:11.000
No, I was going to teach.

00:37:11.000 --> 00:37:13.000
Something is general.

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:15.000
I don't...

00:37:15.000 --> 00:37:17.000
I really don't recall.

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:19.000
I think you would have to ask someone else when I was here.

00:37:19.000 --> 00:37:22.000
It's what I don't think I was.

00:37:23.000 --> 00:37:30.000
I don't think I was as independent of my family as I might have been.

00:37:30.000 --> 00:37:39.000
I think I was always maybe too late thinking, you know, independent of what my mother needed, what my father needed,

00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:41.000
and how we would work together.

00:37:41.000 --> 00:37:47.000
You see, growing up, we all talked about how we're going to all work and we're going to own the land.

00:37:48.000 --> 00:37:52.000
So it was always a we that when we talked about the things we were going to do,

00:37:52.000 --> 00:37:57.000
always at the center of it was we were going to get the land and dad's going to finish paying for the land

00:37:57.000 --> 00:38:01.000
and then we're going to get a car and then we're going to get a big house and then we're going to get...

00:38:01.000 --> 00:38:04.000
And so we...

00:38:04.000 --> 00:38:07.000
We was the propellant there.

00:38:07.000 --> 00:38:09.000
It propelled me in my thinking.

00:38:09.000 --> 00:38:14.000
And I think maybe in 17, I didn't think so much about going off to do anything.

00:38:14.000 --> 00:38:16.000
I knew I was going to teach, I think.

00:38:16.000 --> 00:38:17.000
I was going to...

00:38:17.000 --> 00:38:18.000
Who else was I going to teach?

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:20.000
And why is, of course.

00:38:20.000 --> 00:38:23.000
Let's take this a little quick pause.

00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:25.000
We're rolling.

00:38:25.000 --> 00:38:27.000
We're back on after a short break.

00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:32.000
Dr. Terry, I have just one quick question before we turn towards screens for our independent college.

00:38:32.000 --> 00:38:35.000
Did you happen to know what I'm not thinking the answer would be?

00:38:35.000 --> 00:38:37.000
Did you happen to know Theaoseus Tobias Clayton Sr and Warren?

00:38:37.000 --> 00:38:38.000
Yes.

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:39.000
What you did?

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:40.000
I knew him.

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:42.000
No, so I knew him.

00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:45.000
I met him, I think, when I was in college.

00:38:45.000 --> 00:38:57.000
I think he came to Warren to an Asaloyah and immediately he and his wife Eva became members of our community.

00:38:57.000 --> 00:38:59.000
I knew them.

00:38:59.000 --> 00:39:01.000
I know them.

00:39:01.000 --> 00:39:03.000
He would be...

00:39:03.000 --> 00:39:07.000
Well, I was going to just a minute if I was ready.

00:39:08.000 --> 00:39:11.000
We're back on after a break to tell them.

00:39:11.000 --> 00:39:14.000
Dr. Terry, I know...

00:39:14.000 --> 00:39:20.000
I think I know that your parents drove you to the college here and moved you in and followed 57 years ago.

00:39:20.000 --> 00:39:22.000
Yes, they did.

00:39:22.000 --> 00:39:27.000
What did you discover here in thriving and Hispanic college?

00:39:27.000 --> 00:39:29.000
It was a big day for me.

00:39:29.000 --> 00:39:32.000
For the whole community.

00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:34.000
I came from someplace.

00:39:34.000 --> 00:39:35.000
I just didn't...

00:39:35.000 --> 00:39:40.000
So I came being supported by the whole community.

00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:43.000
They prayed for me at church.

00:39:43.000 --> 00:39:46.000
They gave me a few pennies here and there.

00:39:46.000 --> 00:39:49.000
As I said, we didn't have a lot of money.

00:39:49.000 --> 00:39:52.000
I had a little scholarship.

00:39:52.000 --> 00:39:57.000
SAT.

00:39:58.000 --> 00:40:04.000
I had done well enough to have a little scholarship and I was going to work a little bit.

00:40:04.000 --> 00:40:06.000
But there was always that.

00:40:06.000 --> 00:40:08.000
Let me give you a few pennies.

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:13.000
I came being born up by the good wishes of the community.

00:40:13.000 --> 00:40:17.000
And off we came to Bennett College.

00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:19.000
I'd never been to Bennett College before.

00:40:19.000 --> 00:40:21.000
I'd never been to Greensboro before.

00:40:21.000 --> 00:40:30.000
And I arrived here to have ourselves, you know, just sort of swallowed up my parents and me and all of us.

00:40:30.000 --> 00:40:37.000
But a lot of parents and a lot of students all being deposited by our parents.

00:40:37.000 --> 00:40:43.000
And it was an only feeling when they said goodbye and left.

00:40:43.000 --> 00:40:45.000
It was very lonely.

00:40:45.000 --> 00:40:54.000
Who got some of the people who would, you know, in short order become persons who were important to you here on the campus faculty staff?

00:40:54.000 --> 00:40:55.000
That was me.

00:40:55.000 --> 00:41:03.000
I met when I, as my parents were getting me situated in my room, there was a woman who was bringing her daughter.

00:41:03.000 --> 00:41:13.000
There was a girl, Roslyn Smith, being deposited from West Virginia and her mom met my mom and they talked.

00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:20.000
And Roslyn's mother told my mom how they talked and just told each other so much and so little time I never know.

00:41:20.000 --> 00:41:23.000
But here's what got established in that little while.

00:41:23.000 --> 00:41:28.000
Roslyn's mother had other children in college at the same time.

00:41:28.000 --> 00:41:34.000
And so she immediately knew she told Roslyn immediately she wouldn't be coming home.

00:41:34.000 --> 00:41:36.000
Roslyn's mom wouldn't be coming home.

00:41:36.000 --> 00:41:41.000
There wasn't going to be money to bring Roslyn home except at Christmas time and in the summertime.

00:41:41.000 --> 00:41:53.000
My mom told Mrs. Smith that we lived a couple of hours up the road and they would be driving back to see me often and I could come home quite often.

00:41:53.000 --> 00:41:55.000
I could come home for Thanksgiving.

00:41:55.000 --> 00:41:57.000
I could come home whenever.

00:41:57.000 --> 00:42:02.000
And that Roslyn could come home with me anytime.

00:42:02.000 --> 00:42:08.000
So Mrs. Smith and Mrs. Alexander sort of bonded that day and they exchanged children.

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:14.000
My mom became surrogate, Roslyn's mom and Roslyn's mom became sort of my mom.

00:42:14.000 --> 00:42:20.000
Although it would take a long time before I got to West Virginia to meet Roslyn's mother.

00:42:20.000 --> 00:42:26.000
Roslyn went home with me that very, very first break that we had and she went home with me for all four years.

00:42:26.000 --> 00:42:30.000
My very best friend to this day is Roslyn Smith.

00:42:30.000 --> 00:42:33.000
She is actually living in Greensboro.

00:42:33.000 --> 00:42:40.000
And so she retired here some 10 years ago from New York where she had been working in social works.

00:42:40.000 --> 00:42:44.000
She came back when she retired to Greensboro after she left her.

00:42:44.000 --> 00:42:46.000
She said why did you come back to Greensboro?

00:42:46.000 --> 00:42:48.000
I mean, did Bennett have anything to do with it?

00:42:48.000 --> 00:42:54.000
But she came to Greensboro and then of course when I took the job here I was delighted that she's here.

00:42:54.000 --> 00:42:57.000
So we are where we met.

00:42:57.000 --> 00:43:03.000
She was, as I think I understand, she was really kind of in a different part of campus in the classroom.

00:43:03.000 --> 00:43:04.000
So to speak.

00:43:04.000 --> 00:43:08.000
She studied sociology and political science.

00:43:08.000 --> 00:43:11.000
I was doing English in theater.

00:43:11.000 --> 00:43:16.000
Tell me about the world of being an English student and a theater student at those late 50s.

00:43:16.000 --> 00:43:18.000
Oh my goodness.

00:43:18.000 --> 00:43:19.000
It was wonderful.

00:43:20.000 --> 00:43:24.000
My English professor was Hobart Jarrett.

00:43:24.000 --> 00:43:29.000
Well, I had several, but Dr. Jarrett was the man who taught me literature.

00:43:29.000 --> 00:43:33.000
Dr. Jarrett, what a wonderful man, what a brilliant man.

00:43:33.000 --> 00:43:37.000
All of my faculty were.

00:43:37.000 --> 00:43:39.000
Dr. Jarrett was hard.

00:43:39.000 --> 00:43:40.000
He was tough.

00:43:40.000 --> 00:43:44.000
He ex-exacted absolute perfection.

00:43:44.000 --> 00:43:47.000
And we were arrogant enough to think we could give it to him.

00:43:47.000 --> 00:43:55.000
You know, he really had us just chombed into thinking that we could write anything we could articulate in it.

00:43:55.000 --> 00:43:57.000
We could debate anybody.

00:43:57.000 --> 00:44:03.000
He was just a wonderful teacher and he empowered us a big deal, but no nonsense.

00:44:03.000 --> 00:44:05.000
So I was very much engaged with him.

00:44:05.000 --> 00:44:13.000
He would walk on campus and say, Miss Alexander, I am going to pick up a ball.

00:44:13.000 --> 00:44:14.000
What am I?

00:44:14.000 --> 00:44:17.000
That's a book and I'd say literary history of England.

00:44:17.000 --> 00:44:18.000
He'd say yes.

00:44:18.000 --> 00:44:26.000
I mean, those little games, you know, he would, he would set the show off about how area that he was.

00:44:26.000 --> 00:44:28.000
And we reveled in it.

00:44:28.000 --> 00:44:31.000
He also was a very handsome man.

00:44:31.000 --> 00:44:35.000
And he smoked a pipe and he was so elegant.

00:44:35.000 --> 00:44:41.000
We all, we all just sort of drooled after Dr. Jarrett, but in a nice way.

00:44:41.000 --> 00:44:45.000
We were so, so proud to say we were his students.

00:44:45.000 --> 00:44:46.000
Now that was Dr. Jarrett.

00:44:46.000 --> 00:44:54.000
Then there was Dr. Crawford who taught us grammar.

00:44:54.000 --> 00:44:58.000
He was less, how should I say this?

00:44:58.000 --> 00:45:02.000
He didn't, he was, I don't want to say he was less polished, but he was less polished.

00:45:02.000 --> 00:45:03.000
That's the fact.

00:45:03.000 --> 00:45:04.000
He was less polished.

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:06.000
But he was a terror.

00:45:06.000 --> 00:45:09.000
He didn't like you to spit verbs or anything of that sort.

00:45:09.000 --> 00:45:12.000
So he taught us grammar and he would have us at this sentence.

00:45:12.000 --> 00:45:19.000
He would make us post verbs and he would make us diagram sentences.

00:45:19.000 --> 00:45:22.000
He was, he was tough.

00:45:22.000 --> 00:45:26.000
I wasn't, I don't think I was one of his favorite students.

00:45:26.000 --> 00:45:33.000
But I was, I was treated kindly by him because I could diagram a sentence, you know, and I got out of his way.

00:45:33.000 --> 00:45:37.000
But there, he was, he was serious and you know, you know,

00:45:37.000 --> 00:45:40.000
he was, he was, he was just a serious man.

00:45:40.000 --> 00:45:45.000
And so he wasn't quite like, like Dr., Dr. Hobai Jarrett.

00:45:45.000 --> 00:45:58.000
Then we had, in the theater, we had Fred Eady, who had come to us from Howard.

00:45:58.000 --> 00:46:01.000
I was a terrific director.

00:46:01.000 --> 00:46:03.000
And we got him married.

00:46:03.000 --> 00:46:06.000
We thought he needed to be married.

00:46:06.000 --> 00:46:14.000
We, we selected the lady on the campus that we thought he ought to be married to.

00:46:14.000 --> 00:46:21.000
And so we bought her, we collected money and bought her flowers and sent her flowers and said they were from Mr. Edy.

00:46:21.000 --> 00:46:25.000
But we told him, we told him, we said now we, we took this lady these flowers.

00:46:25.000 --> 00:46:28.000
You should follow up and we put your name on it.

00:46:28.000 --> 00:46:31.000
He did and you want to know something really funny.

00:46:31.000 --> 00:46:33.000
They got married.

00:46:33.000 --> 00:46:35.000
We always took credit for that.

00:46:35.000 --> 00:46:37.000
And they were, they were, they were, they were, they were, they were beautiful.

00:46:37.000 --> 00:46:38.000
What can I say?

00:46:38.000 --> 00:46:42.000
I lived in Honors Dorm, which was, can't talk.

00:46:42.000 --> 00:46:47.000
We were very proud to be Bennett girls.

00:46:47.000 --> 00:46:57.000
Because we were taught every day that we were as good as anybody in the world,

00:46:57.000 --> 00:47:06.000
and better than a lot of people in the world, and had responsibility to help those who were as fortunate as we were.

00:47:06.000 --> 00:47:14.000
That there was something in life that required us to be as good as we could be,

00:47:14.000 --> 00:47:18.000
and to give back to the communities from which we can.

00:47:18.000 --> 00:47:26.000
It was that sense that led us to be cognizant of what was happening in the community,

00:47:26.000 --> 00:47:32.000
of helping people to get registered, of both understanding the importance of registering to vote,

00:47:32.000 --> 00:47:39.000
and getting people to do that, taking ourselves into the community to be helpful,

00:47:39.000 --> 00:47:45.000
to help people in, in the ways that we could, because of food drives.

00:47:45.000 --> 00:47:51.000
The whole sense and to talk about the community, you know, I grew up.

00:47:51.000 --> 00:47:56.000
That's very important, but I'm saying, not to use so much as I've reflect on it,

00:47:56.000 --> 00:48:00.000
why I think it was important to me that they taught us these things,

00:48:00.000 --> 00:48:07.000
is because you see, I talk about having been happy when I was growing up as a youngster.

00:48:07.000 --> 00:48:14.000
What I mean is that I felt safe, that happiness was somehow connected with being safe,

00:48:14.000 --> 00:48:23.000
but I can remind you that in that time, the whole southern terrain was dotted with white-only signs,

00:48:23.000 --> 00:48:30.000
with the signs that said, you know, colors, or negro signs, sort of,

00:48:30.000 --> 00:48:36.000
that sort of, there were reminders that there were places that you couldn't go,

00:48:36.000 --> 00:48:41.000
and the places that you ought not to go if you wanted to be safe.

00:48:41.000 --> 00:48:49.000
Safety was a part of being happy, and that's, and when you were cocooned in safety,

00:48:49.000 --> 00:48:54.000
and you were just such a, and that's what this campus was, this campus was a place

00:48:54.000 --> 00:49:00.000
that we knew that we were taken care of, and now we were asked to give,

00:49:00.000 --> 00:49:05.000
all we could give in the classes, but we also knew that we were special.

00:49:05.000 --> 00:49:10.000
And that is why it was inevitable that we entered into the city.

00:49:10.000 --> 00:49:12.000
We knew they were wrong.

00:49:12.000 --> 00:49:21.000
You see, you can't have someone inside the gates being taught how they could be the best everybody,

00:49:21.000 --> 00:49:25.000
and anybody, they could be everything, and then walk right out the gate and be told,

00:49:25.000 --> 00:49:27.000
you can't sit here.

00:49:27.000 --> 00:49:32.000
And I think it's very important to know that F.W. Woolworth became,

00:49:32.000 --> 00:49:35.000
and I do, that you can't sit down for a coke.

00:49:35.000 --> 00:49:37.000
Now, you know, you could go into F.W. Woolworth.

00:49:37.000 --> 00:49:42.000
F.W. Woolworth was not, was not closed to black patronage at all.

00:49:42.000 --> 00:49:48.000
You could go into F.W. Woolworth, you could buy anything you wanted, that they sold in F.W. Woolworth that month.

00:49:48.000 --> 00:49:53.000
You just couldn't sit down to get saved, which is the lunch counter.

00:49:53.000 --> 00:49:56.000
So it was the lunch counter. You couldn't sit down there to eat.

00:49:56.000 --> 00:50:04.000
So you see, that stood in stark contrast to all the things that we had going on here at Bennett,

00:50:04.000 --> 00:50:09.000
where we dressed for dinner in the evenings and sat with tablecloths,

00:50:09.000 --> 00:50:15.000
and we learned which fork to use, and how, and we went downtown where it hats,

00:50:15.000 --> 00:50:19.000
and we wore gloves, and we were Bennett College student activists.

00:50:19.000 --> 00:50:23.000
You can see how it wouldn't, it was just such a jarring thing to be told,

00:50:23.000 --> 00:50:27.000
well, Bennett lady, guess what, you can't sit down there and have a cherry coke.

00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:31.000
So those, that, that, they, there were things that got us,

00:50:31.000 --> 00:50:35.000
there was a diseased as it were, there was a dis, dis, dis, eat,

00:50:35.000 --> 00:50:40.000
it's uncomfortable, one cannot square those two things.

00:50:40.000 --> 00:50:43.000
Did you, through these, through your first couple years of college,

00:50:43.000 --> 00:50:48.000
I mean, you, you've been a college student, is, is, is a very encompassing and engaging kind of experience

00:50:48.000 --> 00:50:51.000
when you're happy and thriving in your classes and all.

00:50:51.000 --> 00:50:55.000
What, what portion of your attention is some broad kind of sense?

00:50:55.000 --> 00:50:58.000
Did you give to these wider questions?

00:50:58.000 --> 00:51:06.000
I mean, Little Rock is happening the, the first desegregation of the local Greensboro schools is happening.

00:51:06.000 --> 00:51:07.000
Yes.

00:51:07.000 --> 00:51:16.000
There are some early law suits and moving through the courts filed by people like Dr. Simkin's to try to break down

00:51:16.000 --> 00:51:18.000
barriers of segregation in the city.

00:51:18.000 --> 00:51:19.000
Yes.

00:51:19.000 --> 00:51:26.000
How much of that was, was a part of your, you know, what, what you gave your attention to because there were lots of other things that were keeping on.

00:51:26.000 --> 00:51:28.000
That's your work.

00:51:28.000 --> 00:51:39.000
But, but I, I told you a part of Bennett was always that the education that Bennett was to prepare you to, to make a contribution to the world

00:51:39.000 --> 00:51:44.000
and to be reconnected into your community.

00:51:44.000 --> 00:51:53.000
My classmates had experiences before we got here.

00:51:53.000 --> 00:52:04.000
We didn't, even I didn't come here, you know, sort of from Mars where everything was great and we never had a sense that there was, that could be clashes between white and black.

00:52:04.000 --> 00:52:06.000
We all, we all knew about those things.

00:52:06.000 --> 00:52:13.000
I, you know, I grew up here and been knowing about such things, you know, my brothers were, my mother were at all the time about what would happen.

00:52:13.000 --> 00:52:20.000
So, what I mean when I say we were safe is exactly that.

00:52:20.000 --> 00:52:23.000
A storm is going on around us.

00:52:23.000 --> 00:52:27.000
We are aware of the storm, but we can also feel safe in here.

00:52:27.000 --> 00:52:35.000
And that's when I meant when I said that safety was a very important part of how I, I think, became, was a healthy,

00:52:35.000 --> 00:52:38.000
was a healthy person because I look back over it, I think I was healthy.

00:52:38.000 --> 00:52:44.000
I think, I think I mean a healthy ego, a healthy psyche going up in that.

00:52:44.000 --> 00:52:47.000
I don't think it damaged me in any way.

00:52:47.000 --> 00:52:58.000
Now I might be wrong, but I don't, I don't think I grew up with my, my mother was Wise, North Carolina and she would talk about these things to us precisely so that they wouldn't scare us so much.

00:52:58.000 --> 00:53:00.000
Or they would, we would know how to live with them.

00:53:00.000 --> 00:53:03.000
My mother would tell us, she didn't want us to hate white people.

00:53:03.000 --> 00:53:07.000
Now mother, my mother had this room. She wouldn't let us say they when we talked about white people.

00:53:07.000 --> 00:53:09.000
She wouldn't let us say they did so.

00:53:09.000 --> 00:53:18.000
So, one day she took a piece of chalk and she wrote T, H, E, Y, and then she erased the T on the one hand and she erased the Y and she said,

00:53:18.000 --> 00:53:21.000
you come and tell me what he did.

00:53:21.000 --> 00:53:31.000
You named him and you named her and we will deal with that, but you will not ever speak of all white people as bad or haven't you,

00:53:31.000 --> 00:53:34.000
you're bad and you see we had, we understood that.

00:53:34.000 --> 00:53:39.000
So, we couldn't afford to be shielded from what was happening in the world.

00:53:39.000 --> 00:53:46.000
I just am always grateful that my parents taught us, I think, the best way to negotiate it.

00:53:46.000 --> 00:53:56.000
And she told my son, as I said, I have one son, and he's always so pleased to remind me that when he was home talking to his grandma,

00:53:56.000 --> 00:54:00.000
he told her something about some white people doing something.

00:54:00.000 --> 00:54:05.000
Grandma, why did you let them do that?

00:54:05.000 --> 00:54:09.000
Why do you let them call you Mary and you come?

00:54:09.000 --> 00:54:15.000
She says, Mike, you know, they're as good as they know how to be.

00:54:15.000 --> 00:54:18.000
What are you going to do with that?

00:54:18.000 --> 00:54:20.000
They're as good as they know how to be.

00:54:20.000 --> 00:54:29.000
And so, there was a way that she, my mother allowed us to have an ego about who we were and she wouldn't let anybody damage that.

00:54:29.000 --> 00:54:31.000
So, we were just told.

00:54:31.000 --> 00:54:35.000
They're, they're about, she said to Mike, they're as good as they know how to be.

00:54:35.000 --> 00:54:37.000
What were you going to do with that?

00:54:37.000 --> 00:54:39.000
Then, they're as good as they know how to be.

00:54:39.000 --> 00:54:46.000
But to come back to your question, so here, yes, we had Dr. Edmunds, we had Roslyn and my friend was in sociology.

00:54:46.000 --> 00:54:50.000
They didn't talk about, I mean, we had a life out there.

00:54:50.000 --> 00:54:52.000
They talked about issues.

00:54:52.000 --> 00:54:56.000
We talked in our classes about what was happening in the world.

00:54:56.000 --> 00:55:01.000
We didn't pretend that the world wasn't out there.

00:55:01.000 --> 00:55:05.000
I think you missed Dr. King's appearance on the campus in 58, is that correct?

00:55:05.000 --> 00:55:07.000
Yes.

00:55:07.000 --> 00:55:22.000
By 59, especially Fall of 59, of course, the momentum is gathering and we'll, we'll soon lead to some direct action protests.

00:55:22.000 --> 00:55:34.000
What do you think about the Fall of 59 and some of the women here on the campus, of course, were talking very actively, as you've just been saying, and really thinking very hard about this question?

00:55:34.000 --> 00:55:52.000
Well, it's really started in the, in the, my classmates who were in sociology classes, they were with sociology, Roslyn, Smith, Gwen, Gwen Mackel, Shirley, Dismute, that group, Gloria Brown.

00:55:52.000 --> 00:55:59.000
They were the ones that were engaged, engaged in, in an intense way.

00:55:59.000 --> 00:56:05.000
But you see, they would come back to the dorms and tell us what was happening.

00:56:05.000 --> 00:56:08.000
And as I say, Roslyn was my best friend.

00:56:08.000 --> 00:56:11.000
We knew what was going on.

00:56:11.000 --> 00:56:19.000
We knew, and you start as a theoretical, how do we conduct ourselves in the world, if that is the case?

00:56:19.000 --> 00:56:22.000
And then someone says, why don't, what would happen if we boycott it?

00:56:22.000 --> 00:56:27.000
What would happen if that, how can these barriers be torn down?

00:56:27.000 --> 00:56:31.000
These were questions over being asked. You know, there had been sittings before.

00:56:31.000 --> 00:56:35.000
Greensboro.

00:56:35.000 --> 00:56:38.000
There had been protests before. There had been marches before.

00:56:38.000 --> 00:56:53.000
Bennett College student activists and the showing of the film, The Birth of a Nation, which is a pretty ugly film.

00:56:53.000 --> 00:56:55.000
You've done voter registration for the rest of the day.

00:56:55.000 --> 00:56:57.000
In its stories, we had done voter registration.

00:56:57.000 --> 00:57:05.000
So I cannot tell you exactly and precisely what moment, you know, that was this great epiphany and we did things.

00:57:05.000 --> 00:57:14.000
But what I end up knowing was that students were planning and talking about a boycott.

00:57:14.000 --> 00:57:19.000
Going downtown and picketing.

00:57:19.000 --> 00:57:27.000
What would happen if they picketed, what would happen, and then it went from picketing to, well, what would happen if we sat down at the lunch counter.

00:57:27.000 --> 00:57:35.000
So these were conversations that were being talked about students, which talked about nonviolence.

00:57:35.000 --> 00:57:47.000
That's exactly what, that's a route that people don't talk of, remember, that these students were, we were, Dr. Edmunds and our faculty talked about nonviolence?

00:57:47.000 --> 00:57:52.000
You remember King was talking about non-violence, all of a sudden, nonviolence?

00:57:52.000 --> 00:57:57.000
If somebody hits you, you hit them back, you know, if it's supposed to be associated with that.

00:57:57.000 --> 00:58:01.000
How do you conduct yourself? Is it dangerous, you know, what happened?

00:58:01.000 --> 00:58:08.000
So it was in the air and we were here on the campus and yes, we talked about those things.

00:58:08.000 --> 00:58:19.000
Do you think that these, you described the name to group of women who were very much active in these kinds of conversations on the campus and friends of yours?

00:58:19.000 --> 00:58:29.000
Do you think that among those women there is a sense that they were, well, I don't know if I'm going to answer this way.

00:58:29.000 --> 00:58:53.000
To what extent would they think they ought to be placed in the, how much should they be credited for the full realization that impulse here in the community among students and now we're reaching over across to North Carolina A&T State University, that opened the door to direct action process?

00:58:53.000 --> 00:58:55.000
Are they credited sufficiently, I guess, as well?

00:58:55.000 --> 00:58:56.000
They would say not.

00:58:56.000 --> 00:58:57.000
They would say not.

00:58:57.000 --> 00:58:58.000
They would say not.

00:58:58.000 --> 00:59:20.000
Back in two years ago, I, for the 50th anniversary of the Greensboro sit-ins, I was here and as a new provost and I remembered those days.

00:59:20.000 --> 00:59:38.000
So I called a group of them to come back to talk about that and so we had a retrospective when Gwen Mackel came, Shirley disney came, Dolores Finger came, Roslyn Smith came, Linda Brown was here.

00:59:38.000 --> 00:59:49.000
We had, we talked, we were in the chapel and we talked about that and they would say no.

00:59:49.000 --> 00:59:51.000
Here's how they talk about it.

00:59:51.000 --> 01:00:03.000
They say that they indeed did not argue with the fact that the four young men at North Carolina A&T State University were the first to sit down.

01:00:03.000 --> 01:00:21.000
But they say that it was not spontaneous, that it had come, that action had been born of a plan, that had been carefully, carefully considered and deliberated beginning here on Bennett's campus with the girls.

01:00:21.000 --> 01:00:41.000
And that they had in fact been happily considering it and Dr. Jarrett said to them, well, you girls shouldn't get engaged in doing that alone because, you know, this is the girls must be protected.

01:00:41.000 --> 01:00:54.000
So they were encouraged to invite the North Carolina A&T State University boys to sit with them and to plan this, just sit in and what it would be because you see we're talking about something that could be very dangerous.

01:00:54.000 --> 01:01:05.000
Nobody asked their parents, our parents did not send us down here to go do that, you hear me? And they would not have been happy maybe. Some of them might have.

01:01:05.000 --> 01:01:11.000
My classmates have wonderful stories about their lives.

01:01:11.000 --> 01:01:22.000
Green Mackels parents had been run out of Mississippi because of her dad's political action. These young women weren't babes in the woods.

01:01:22.000 --> 01:01:30.000
My own father had had his problems.

01:01:30.000 --> 01:01:37.000
We had early dissimuse and she just couldn't figure out, nobody had ever asked her to sit in the back of a bus or anything.

01:01:37.000 --> 01:01:44.000
So we all came with a real deep feeling that that's wrong. That's wrong and we knew that.

01:01:44.000 --> 01:01:53.000
So they wanted to correct it and to be educated and not do anything about it was not the education wasn't going to mean very much.

01:01:53.000 --> 01:02:04.000
So these girls would tell you that they worked very hard, they discussed everything and they can tell you that Dr. Willa B. Player, our president was involved as well.

01:02:04.000 --> 01:02:17.000
Dr. Willa B. Player was told and Dr. Willa B. Player said she couldn't tell us not to her girls. We were always called her girls. She couldn't tell her girls not to engage in that.

01:02:17.000 --> 01:02:30.000
But she did point out that it would be kind of folly to start the Greensboro sit-ins, to start the action before the Christmas vacation.

01:02:30.000 --> 01:02:40.000
And so if you started it, it Thanksgiving, say for instance, and then everybody would say sorry, I've been politically active but I've got to go home now and I'll come back. I'll see you after the vacation.

01:02:40.000 --> 01:02:47.000
So she said she cautioned them to wait and they did.

01:02:47.000 --> 01:02:54.000
And then it told a lot of us when they came back that they were all ready to start and they came back and on February 1st was it?

01:02:54.000 --> 01:03:03.000
The young men sat down. Now here's an important thing I asked when, Gwen Mackel, when, where were you on that day?

01:03:03.000 --> 01:03:08.000
When they sat down she said I was in Woolworths.

01:03:08.000 --> 01:03:12.000
Why were you there? She said because we were there.

01:03:12.000 --> 01:03:22.000
But first you had to go buy something. You said we knew how to do it. You had to go because we had been trained that if you didn't buy something you could be tossed out of the store.

01:03:22.000 --> 01:03:32.000
So you go in and store you buy something. And she says I was standing and waiting because it was a plan.

01:03:32.000 --> 01:03:47.000
And it did not, it was a plan that had been created here on the campus and so the girls would think that they did not get enough credit. That's what they would think.

01:03:47.000 --> 01:03:59.000
Very quickly many other students take places at the lunch counter and there are carpools and careful assignment of rotating shifts of students and all in.

01:03:59.000 --> 01:04:02.000
And you sat down there too.

01:04:02.000 --> 01:04:05.000
Yes I do. Besides Linda Brown.

01:04:05.000 --> 01:04:26.000
I think we might have been young because honestly I felt proud.

01:04:26.000 --> 01:04:37.000
I don't think my mother ever felt, maybe she felt proud but I think that was not her main feeling. I think she was terrified.

01:04:37.000 --> 01:04:49.000
I know that now because I have a child and I mean I have a son who's not a child anymore. He's a very big role man but even so I think as a mother I would be afraid but I'm going to tell you we were proud.

01:04:49.000 --> 01:04:59.000
I was very proud. I would tell you something else.

01:04:59.000 --> 01:05:12.000
I never ever understood the hatred that came. It was absolutely surprising because I did not understand what people would glare at us with such hatred.

01:05:12.000 --> 01:05:22.000
That was a little unnerving but I was basically very proud to have done that.

01:05:22.000 --> 01:05:36.000
Did you are unloading about it? Did your parents have any words of guidance for you or come on tour?

01:05:36.000 --> 01:05:51.000
It was interesting enough my parents, my mother never talked to me about that very much. She was very quiet. My mom was never very quiet but my mom didn't talk about that very much.

01:05:51.000 --> 01:06:09.000
I think I understand why. I think my mom didn't want to say I wish you hadn't done it. I think my mom regretted the world as it was that it had to be done but I don't think my mom was related to that.

01:06:09.000 --> 01:06:24.000
I think my mom would have forgiven me if I had called in sick. I think she might have. I don't think she would have been too upset if I had called in sick but she never ever let me know from her own words what she felt.

01:06:24.000 --> 01:06:27.000
She was just quiet.

01:06:27.000 --> 01:06:42.000
It was interesting if you would maybe just say a few words about her because as you've already said she made clear in certain unmistakable ways.

01:06:42.000 --> 01:06:55.000
Let me back on after short break. I want to ask a little bit for your thoughts and perspective on Dr. Willa B. Player in Perl here at Bennett College.

01:06:55.000 --> 01:07:11.000
I think I'm going to talk about the leadership at North Carolina A&T State University because of course the institutions have separate histories, many similar general crowd aspects of the history but also different relations to the state of North Carolina etc.

01:07:11.000 --> 01:07:23.000
To talk a little bit about the education leadership in that era and the forces active upon that leadership.

01:07:23.000 --> 01:07:39.000
Dr. Willa B. Player was, let me first tell you a little bit about Dr. Willa B. Player. She was a big, big, big woman and I don't mean in statue, I mean in physical statue.

01:07:39.000 --> 01:07:50.000
In the shadow she cast over the campus when she walked and she was quiet. She was a very, very, very dignified woman.

01:07:50.000 --> 01:08:03.000
But we all believe, not I, we all believe that she was profoundly committed to making Bennett women.

01:08:03.000 --> 01:08:14.000
The girls who came to Bennett and to women who could stand in the world strong women with a commitment to social justice.

01:08:14.000 --> 01:08:24.000
Now that, I don't mean just to being good English teachers, being good, you know, math teachers, being good physicists.

01:08:24.000 --> 01:08:31.000
I mean undergirding all of that with a profound sense of social justice.

01:08:31.000 --> 01:08:45.000
And that was her, I mean and she, she talked about that but quietly in her philosophy she talked about the fact that education was no good if you didn't use it to correct wrongs in society.

01:08:45.000 --> 01:09:01.000
She just believed that and so she didn't make fiery speeches about that. She wasn't a fiery speech in person but she was very quietly committed and you knew when you were in her presence that it was not just nonsense that she was talking.

01:09:01.000 --> 01:09:14.000
She really believed and lived what she talked about. So I play it was a really, really brave woman and if she cared about anybody, she cared about what the legacy that she would pass on.

01:09:14.000 --> 01:09:19.000
She would pass on to us at Bennett College. She was an incredible woman so that's got to play her.

01:09:19.000 --> 01:09:35.000
I don't know very much about the leadership at North Carolina A&T State University but I do know that whatever is said and written about the movement here as it played itself out in Greensboro,

01:09:35.000 --> 01:09:44.000
Bennett College women were involved in it from the top down and we were supported and we were encouraged and so the college was there.

01:09:44.000 --> 01:09:48.000
It was what we learned as the college is what we were brought together to do as the college.

01:09:48.000 --> 01:09:54.000
Now I don't know what, and Dr. Willa B. Player and we knew she was looking over us. We knew she was monitoring us.

01:09:55.000 --> 01:10:07.000
We knew for instance, we knew she said that we could go down and march and sit down and sit at the lunch counter but we would have to turn in our grades.

01:10:07.000 --> 01:10:23.000
There was no faculty member was to give us excuses. When I was in Amherst, the kids used to ask when they went off to march on a protest or something they'd come and asked the professors to overlook the fact that they were in the office.

01:10:23.000 --> 01:10:30.000
They were there to forgive their bad reasons and you don't do that. That's not a political stance.

01:10:30.000 --> 01:10:41.000
You're not giving up anything. If you're not willing to risk your grades or to walk out and take a D to go do something and you don't mean it very much.

01:10:41.000 --> 01:10:54.000
So here we knew that this was something real, it was profound and it was sort of like, it was like Dr. Willa B. Player was here with us all the way and we knew with that.

01:10:54.000 --> 01:11:05.000
And anybody who saw us knew that we came from there, they could trace us all the way back to where Bennett started and that was what I could say about Dr. Willa B. Player.

01:11:05.000 --> 01:11:12.000
I don't know very much about who was, I don't even know who the name of the president that they and T was.

01:11:12.000 --> 01:11:24.000
I can suspect that he didn't spend a lot of time, that his young people down there for me and T was spending a lot of time being supported and encouraged by the president.

01:11:24.000 --> 01:11:38.000
I don't know but I said that but I can believe to my heart that he probably wanted the Greensboro sit-ins to be successful.

01:11:38.000 --> 01:11:54.000
I can believe in my heart that he wanted those Greensboro sit-ins to be very successful and whether or not he was able to say, I don't know, but at there as you say, there are different relationships that people had with the state and with being funded by the state.

01:11:54.000 --> 01:12:06.000
But Dr. Willa B. Player, you see, we were private. We were private and if you ask, every one of us would tell you, I think if we hadn't been private, I do believe Dr. Willa B. Player would have done exactly what she did.

01:12:06.000 --> 01:12:14.000
I cannot prove that but I believe that because it was so much a part of her.

01:12:14.000 --> 01:12:24.000
Later, you must know this story that when the girls were arrested during the second wave, they were put in jail.

01:12:24.000 --> 01:12:31.000
She got in her car and drove down. Now she didn't get a driver to take her downtown.

01:12:31.000 --> 01:12:40.000
She got in her car alone and drove downtown to go and to say, these are my girls, I brought them there, homework. I want to see after them. I want to see what they were doing.

01:12:40.000 --> 01:12:47.000
I believe she would have taken risk. Risk that others did not and would not have taken.

01:12:47.000 --> 01:13:02.000
I don't think that she would have judged them for that. I believe Dr. Willa B. Player would not have become the enemy of anybody at any one of these institutions because they did what they did.

01:13:02.000 --> 01:13:14.000
I think she would simply say, you must understand. I do what I have to do and that's the difference between us. I think that's the difference in how I would say Dr. Willa B. Player.

01:13:14.000 --> 01:13:22.000
I don't think you actually said the word. She went to the jail to see the men that were arrested.

01:13:22.000 --> 01:13:35.000
That's a very dangerous, black woman in a car. A lot of people in Greensboro did not like what was happening and to see this woman.

01:13:35.000 --> 01:13:49.000
There had been a crossburn. She did have a crossburned at the college president's house. Dr. Willa B. Player was a committed and a sincere soldier. She really was.

01:13:49.000 --> 01:14:04.000
Let me turn your attention to graduation and beyond because of course that spring then. spring of '61 graduation.

01:14:04.000 --> 01:14:21.000
I'm very interested to have you describe your ambition and your experience in UNC-Chapel Hill-Chapel Hill.

01:14:21.000 --> 01:14:29.000
I think I have a lot of things to ask about that. Let me invite you to begin that story.

01:14:29.000 --> 01:14:41.000
At that time I didn't know so much when I came to Bennett as a freshman about what I wanted to do. I wanted to teach. I went back home and teach and Wise, North Carolina.

01:14:41.000 --> 01:14:55.000
By the time I had studied with Dr. Jarrett and Dr. Crawford, I wanted to do really, really I wanted to work in the middle. I wanted to be an English teacher. I wanted to study English.

01:14:55.000 --> 01:15:17.000
I knew that I needed to go to graduate school. At least I had been encouraged by Dr. Jarrett to go to graduate school. Dr. Crawford and Dr. Elizabeth Soel who came later. She thought I wrote well and that always pleased me. She said go to. She was an English woman.

01:15:17.000 --> 01:15:31.000
She was a late-to-been and I think she worked at UNC Greensboro. Until that time I never could figure out how this worked.

01:15:31.000 --> 01:15:46.000
If one wanted to go to graduate school prior to that, prior to my time was coming and it was just changing when I entered UNC Greensboro just beginning to change. If one were black you could apply to the state.

01:15:46.000 --> 01:15:56.000
After you had been accepted at a Northern University, on the state of course would pay your way. Now of course we...

01:15:56.000 --> 01:16:12.000
So as to avoid the obligation to desegregate and to have you in the classes there. So we know that history. James Meredith, Ole Miss and all of that.

01:16:12.000 --> 01:16:27.000
My father and mother said to me, if you want to go to graduate school, I'm a taxpayer. My dad said go to chapel.

01:16:27.000 --> 01:16:43.000
So and this was my mom really pushed this idea. Go to UNC-Chapel Hill-Chapel Hill. Now this is after the Greensboro sit-ins you see and all of that. So now it's go to UNC-Chapel Hill-Chapel Hill. I think my mom thought all right she can do it. She's okay.

01:16:43.000 --> 01:17:05.000
So mom was a little less tense. Well I should never talk to me about Bennett and Greensboro sit-ins. She did say she wanted me to go to UNC-Chapel Hill-Chapel Hill. And she said, because you'll be nearer home and I didn't believe that. I thought she was kind of proud that I would go to UNC-Chapel Hill-Chapel Hill. So I did. I went to UNC-Chapel Hill-Chapel Hill.

01:17:05.000 --> 01:17:25.000
There's a funny story about UNC-Chapel Hill-Chapel Hill. I left here and I went to Hartford, Connecticut where I lived with my sister and brother-in-law. And I worked as a waitress there. But my sister took all of my money. She took all of my money every week. She'd take my money.

01:17:25.000 --> 01:17:39.000
And then when I came back, God read it to come back to UNC-Chapel Hill-Chapel Hill. She gave me my money. That was enforced savings. And she took my shop and all of my sisters and brothers were always very kind to me.

01:17:39.000 --> 01:18:00.000
Well, I came home and then before I got home, I had called to UNC-Chapel Hill-Chapel Hill to ask to apply for graduate housing. And I was going to stay in the dorm. And yes, and they asked, did I fill out the form? They mailed it to me. To Hartford, I mailed it back. And yes, I would like a roommate.

01:18:00.000 --> 01:18:13.000
And so they sent me my room assignment and said, I should appear. It's a certain place on a certain day to pick up the key. And I sent forward my deposit, et cetera.

01:18:13.000 --> 01:18:28.000
So on that day, my dad took me and my mom and my brother. We drove down. My sister, we drove down and I went to the place. And I said, I'm Mr. Alexander. I'm here to get my key. And there was a look of absolute,

01:18:28.000 --> 01:18:49.000
a consternation on the woman's face. And she finally said, you can't be Esther Alexander. Well, and that kind of confused me on my dad. Because, you know, yes, I am. Mr. Alexander, as it turned out, you know what she had done. She had not known that I was black. And she had paired me with a white roommate.

01:18:49.000 --> 01:18:59.000
And there was a ruling at UNC-Chapel Hill-Chapel Hill at that time that that was not to be. So she didn't quite know what to do with me.

01:18:59.000 --> 01:19:14.000
Now, I thought, oh boy, this is not the best way to enter school. But I learned something that day. And my mom, and I talked about it a lot.

01:19:15.000 --> 01:19:29.000
They kept me inside. And eventually, they came and said, now you have your room. Your room is ready. And I said to my mom, as we went down here, I said, well, I'm going to be the only person in that room.

01:19:29.000 --> 01:19:58.000
She said, yes, I expect so. But, and I would have, I was prepared to just be furious. I think I was. But on the way there, there were white girls sitting on suitcases because they didn't have very much spaced housing space for a graduate student. And they would have to go into city someplace.

01:19:58.000 --> 01:20:11.000
Those girls were from I don't know where. But they were saying to me, do you have a roommate? Do you want me to come back? Do you want to like a roommate? Would you like a roommate? I'd be happy to have a room with you.

01:20:11.000 --> 01:20:21.000
And the less than I learned, and my mom and I talked about it when we got in our room, she said, this is not the girls. And you have to remember that this is my mother saying, there is good as they know how to be.

01:20:21.000 --> 01:20:41.000
My mother said, it's not the girls. It's the law. It's the ruling. It's the ruling that you hate. Don't hate the girls. She was right. I met some good friends there. They were never like Ross and Smith because they could come to a certain point in friendship.

01:20:41.000 --> 01:20:55.000
And there were doorways they couldn't cross or wouldn't let themselves cross. And I probably wouldn't let mine cross either. But they didn't do me harm. And they didn't wish me harm.

01:20:55.000 --> 01:21:03.000
And I managed to get a master's degree at UNC-Chapel Hill-Chapel Hill without much fanfare.

01:21:03.000 --> 01:21:12.000
The faculty and the academic experience. So, I took a class with C. C. Hugh Holman.

01:21:13.000 --> 01:21:28.000
Remember C. C. Hugh Holman? Brawl Hibbert Holman's handbook to English literature. I was fortunate to have a class with him. He was a brilliant man, a charming man, and a gentleman.

01:21:28.000 --> 01:21:36.000
My faculty members there were gentlemen. And I didn't have a woman. It's not interesting. I just thought about that.

01:21:36.000 --> 01:21:45.000
I didn't have that was not one course that I took there. But I was only there to get the master's. I'm just going to tell you I didn't want to stay for it.

01:21:45.000 --> 01:21:54.000
I had to go to work. I had to go to the master's. I'd been in school too long. I needed to take off. I couldn't stay and go straight through. I needed to have a break. So I did.

01:21:54.000 --> 01:22:05.000
And then I went to St. Custon College and taught for a couple of years. I really did. If I was going to do this work, I really did need to get the doctorate.

01:22:05.000 --> 01:22:10.000
And so I went off to and ended up getting the doctorate at UMass Amherst.

01:22:10.000 --> 01:22:15.000
Let's take just a little break.

01:22:15.000 --> 01:22:27.000
Okay, Dr. Terry, we're back on after a short break and kind of our last segment here. I want to ask about some of your experiences up in Amherst specifically around.

01:22:27.000 --> 01:22:36.000
And there's so much we have limited time. So I'll skip past other things that would readily merit a whole separate interview. And forgive me for that.

01:22:36.000 --> 01:22:46.000
I want to ask about 69 the creation of African American Studies program at UMass Amherst Amherst. And you would of course direct that program for a couple of decades.

01:22:46.000 --> 01:22:53.000
Yeah, but not at the beginning. Not be right. You got to be at she 74. So later you would step into that role.

01:22:53.000 --> 01:23:03.000
But that was I think one of two programs at the time that was created. It's kind of a capstone to your ten years program and former chair.

01:23:03.000 --> 01:23:13.000
You'd be one of the very first two. I think in the first two in the nation to offer a PhD African American. So broad theme.

01:23:13.000 --> 01:23:26.000
But I'm interested in kind of both the creation of the foundation period and how you thought about the pedagogical challenge, the frameworks, the narratives, the broad theme.

01:23:26.000 --> 01:23:42.000
Well, where do you want me to start? Massachusetts was. There was easy in Massachusetts. I think what happened in Massachusetts could not have happened at other places. And I'll tell you why.

01:23:42.000 --> 01:23:53.000
We had a very, very, very sympathetic administration on the campus.

01:23:53.000 --> 01:24:07.000
There were some things that had happened at and in the in the college community of faculty and friends. It was an incredible assembly of people there.

01:24:07.000 --> 01:24:27.000
First of all, in 1959, the Massachusetts had the UMass Amherst press had come forward with the Massachusetts review. That's the college littleware magazine.

01:24:27.000 --> 01:24:43.000
Read the pages of that magazine and it's almost it's it's eerie because when that magazine was launched, it was dedicated to the four young men who watched it.

01:24:43.000 --> 01:24:55.000
It referenced the four young men who had sat down at North Carolina's North Carolina A&T State University University in the 19th, the 19th.

01:24:55.000 --> 01:25:16.000
It committed itself to have been a magazine. The pages of which would be readily available to black writers, to young black writers in the in the country as they expressed themselves and their traditions. It was an amazing thing.

01:25:16.000 --> 01:25:28.000
I did not know that. I had no way of knowing that. But the group of people who had started the Massachusetts review would become my family almost when I got to UMass Amherst.

01:25:28.000 --> 01:25:38.000
When I got to UMass Amherst, there were very few black people on that campus. That didn't bother me by now.

01:25:38.000 --> 01:25:48.000
I was there to study to get the doctorate. I was an older woman now. I'm all of 22. I'm all of 22. I'm a grown woman now.

01:25:48.000 --> 01:25:58.000
Actually, I was really 25. When I got there, but I was able now, I think I'm certainly grown. I'm able to handle this time.

01:25:58.000 --> 01:26:10.000
I got there. At the same time, I got there. Michael Thelwell came. Then Bernard W. Bell was there. My husband to be Eugene Terry was there.

01:26:10.000 --> 01:26:19.000
We were black people now. Let me tell you that we were 50% of all black people on the campus at that time.

01:26:19.000 --> 01:26:31.000
How do we get there? We got there because Sterling A. Brown out of Howard University had been sending his graduate students.

01:26:31.000 --> 01:26:38.000
We were writing to him saying we want to go study at Howard University. He said, no, no, no, no, no. You don't want to study with me.

01:26:38.000 --> 01:26:54.000
You need to study. You really want to study literature. You really want to put American literature. You need to go study with Sidney Kaplan, who knows more about black American literature and how it fits than in American literature than anybody I know.

01:26:54.000 --> 01:27:08.000
He had sent us all there. Sterling had sent us all there. We used to say we were Sterling's old gang and folk there. Sidney Kaplan, of course, was a graduate program there.

01:27:08.000 --> 01:27:25.000
As soon as he got to be the head of the graduate program in the English department, he's a graduate program director. He's the one who's going to select students. He had written to Sterling and said, send me students. Sydney had been a part of creating the Massachusetts review.

01:27:25.000 --> 01:27:42.000
Now he's a graduate program director in the English department. So he says send me some students. And we all got there to be students. And the first thing we started to be involved in, of course, was a program, not a department, a program under the ages of the English department.

01:27:42.000 --> 01:28:01.000
We started the match. You know, we started and we had we would go visit the homes in the evenings of the professors and the staff people who ran the Massachusetts review. It was a wonderful, wonderful place to be at that time because politics was everything.

01:28:01.000 --> 01:28:18.000
We talked about the world. We talked about making it better. We talked about obligation to make it better. Michael Thelwell had come from the movement. He had been involved in getting the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party up in Atlantic City with Julian Julian Bond.

01:28:18.000 --> 01:28:32.000
It was just the most amazing, amazing assembly of people. And then we talked about what would a program look like that would infuse. And here is what we always talked about.

01:28:32.000 --> 01:28:49.000
We never talked about erasing American literature. We talked about embellishing it with the story of the African American in that contribution.

01:28:49.000 --> 01:29:11.000
So ours was an American story. And we wanted that ours would have to fulfill what was the narrative of the Black person would be a narrative that belonged in the consideration of narratives for the American literature, what was uniquely American.

01:29:11.000 --> 01:29:23.000
We always talked about that. And then we had a program. And then the next thing we knew we were talking about it. We were talking about a department. And so we went.

01:29:23.000 --> 01:29:40.000
Amherst (UMass Amherst) is the flagship, but the president's office was in Boston. So when we went to talk about when my colleagues went to talk about the establishment of such a thing to the president and to the board of trustees, we were never alone.

01:29:40.000 --> 01:29:57.000
We never were not one thing happened at UMass Amherst of protests. Even when the kids were protesting or whatever, there was never one such action that had all Black kids and only Black kids, some only Black faculty involved.

01:29:57.000 --> 01:30:17.000
So we had a wonderful assemblage of people who were there to work with us and to stand by us and to help us with that. And so it was easy. So I'd love to tell people that if you know what was happening at Cornell, what was happening all over the place where fights were breaking out and there were others.

01:30:17.000 --> 01:30:45.000
Today that we were granted the rights to establish our independent department. And after American studies, people kind of yond and voted it and went on and nobody, nothing was blown up. It was a real quiet thing. And I felt kind of, you know, I thought, we're, let down. We wanted there to be some protests. Well, it's not protest.

01:30:45.000 --> 01:31:09.000
Let there be some celebratory noise of some kind, but it was like, it's okay. It's all right. I think UMass Amherst was a very special place for me. I spent a long time there in my career, grew a lot there and got to learn so much more than I ever learned because, because we're there with thresholds that I thought I couldn't.

01:31:09.000 --> 01:31:38.000
And other people thought I couldn't pass at say a UNC-Chapel Hill-Chapel Hill. I was pulled across those in many ways, and UMass Amherst. And so it was, it was a really, if I look back at what I, what I had done in terms of how it just worked right to be the end, it just worked absolutely right. And I was able to join with people black and white to make sure that we had a program that's a good program.

01:31:39.000 --> 01:32:04.000
That's a program that talks about making what was existent in the out of the tower better because it would be, it would, it would not now have to close off classes. We opened doors and we knew that we had students who could do that. We knew that we had a country that needed to understand that and who could swallow that and grow from it.

01:32:04.000 --> 01:32:14.000
That's what we thought. That's what we did and we have a great program at UMass Amherst and I was very, very sad to leave it, but I needed to.

01:32:14.000 --> 01:32:20.000
Just the final question. There is a nice kind of closing of a circle when you come back as provost here.

01:32:20.000 --> 01:32:22.000
Yeah, that's from back as provost.

01:32:22.000 --> 01:32:33.000
2009, and just interested in maybe a final thought or a reflection on Bennett today and how it stands in the lives of the young women who are here now and in the community.

01:32:33.000 --> 01:32:50.000
It's a small, everything has changed because it's, when I was here, the signs were up. Blacks, this way, whites this way, don't come in.

01:32:50.000 --> 01:33:01.000
You know, to knock down the signs sometimes lose us not knowing what we have to do and if we're not very careful, we can, we can to think we're free.

01:33:01.000 --> 01:33:09.000
And there are no more things to be done. There are no movements to have. But there are now. There are, there are economic considerations.

01:33:09.000 --> 01:33:19.000
And I say to the young women who come to me, who want to know, Dr., what you do when we sit down, did you sit down? I say, well, you know, you only can run the relay.

01:33:19.000 --> 01:33:31.000
You run the lap you're in. And then you pass it on. But when you pass it, that person doesn't, doesn't get to run the lap that you ran. That lap's been run.

01:33:31.000 --> 01:33:40.000
You have to run another lap. You have to run your lap. So I say to the students here that the world now is different. It's not the same as it was.

01:33:40.000 --> 01:33:53.000
But it also is not perfect yet because it's a far away, the Greensboro even, far away from being perfect. Doesn't have some of the problems that it had, but it has other ones. And they've got to find them.

01:33:53.000 --> 01:34:03.000
Here's what I say to students that you still have the obligation and the responsibility to make social justice and equality apart,

01:34:03.000 --> 01:34:13.000
a partner with you as you develop whatever skills you want to develop and you pursue whatever course of study you want to pursue.

01:34:13.000 --> 01:34:21.000
You have got to be the best. You have got to give you all and you've got to have a part of it committed to giving back to the community.

01:34:21.000 --> 01:34:30.000
I think that. I think that. So I think now I think I go through here and young people got Twitter and technology. But I can't stand Twitter.

01:34:30.000 --> 01:34:41.000
I, you know, it's so limited. I don't do Twitter. And I try very hard to stay away from blogging and all of that. But you know, the students have to do that.

01:34:41.000 --> 01:34:49.000
And I have to know enough about it to get through. Their world has got to put all of this novel change.

01:34:49.000 --> 01:34:58.000
It's also ingested in many ways and unequal in many ways. And if they're not careful, they won't see it.

01:34:58.000 --> 01:35:10.000
So they've got to work really hard to do that. And I think then it is a good place to be. I think Bennett can become a haven for at least 900 little girls to make a minute.

01:35:10.000 --> 01:35:17.000
To make them into big women. That's what I work to do. And I don't plan to be here forever to have another career.

01:35:17.000 --> 01:35:22.000
But it's certainly a good thing to do on the days that I am.

01:35:22.000 --> 01:35:29.000
It's a real honor and a real privilege. Thank you so much for this opportunity. It's just a lovely view. Thank you.

